  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Makes money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Established specific penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and investigative powers\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized previous money laundering laws\n- Expanded reporting requirements and penalties\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define specific money laundering crimes and associated penalties.\n\nState-level statutes also exist, with many states having their own money laundering laws that complement federal regulations.\n\nThese statutes generally aim to:\n- Detect and prevent illegal financial transactions\n- Trace and prosecute financial crimes\n- Disrupt criminal enterprises\n- Protect the financial system's integrity",
